{"questionId":"15304093","questionHtml":"<p>Hence, by solving the homogeneous differential equation&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>y</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>y</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>,&nbsp;find a general equation that represents this family of curves, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>G</mi></math>. Give your answer in the form <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>d</mi></math> where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>d</mi></math> is a parameter.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>let&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>v</mi><mi>x</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>v</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>attempts to express&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;as a single fraction in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong><em>(M1)</em></strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;(or equivalent)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>(A1)</em></strong></p>\n<p>attempts to separate variables&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong><em> (M1)</em></strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>∫</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>∫</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>x</mi></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>x</mi></math>&nbsp;(or equivalent)</p>\n<p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>ln</mi><mfenced><mrow><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mtext>arc</mtext><mi>tan</mi><mtext>&nbsp;</mtext><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>ln</mi><mfenced open=\"|\" close=\"|\"><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mo>+</mo><mi>d</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;(or equivalent)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>A1A1</em></strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>ln</mi><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mtext>arc</mtext><mi>tan</mi><mfrac><mi>y</mi><mi>x</mi></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mi>ln</mi><mfenced open=\"|\" close=\"|\"><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>d</mi></math>&nbsp;(or equivalent)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong><em> A1</em></strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><strong><em>[9 marks]</em></strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"15304093","referenceCode":"23N.3.AHL.TZ0.2eii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Hence, by solving the homogeneous differential equation dydx=y-xy+x, find a general equation that represents this family of curves, G. Give your answer in the form hx, y=d where d ","paper":"3","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 9]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","AHL 5.18—1st order DE’s – Euler method, variables separable, integrating factor, homogeneous DE using sub y=vx"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}